body:
Browserify offers the ability to provide file contents through a stream but you can also set a `basedir` option. This would be useful especially for those using the javascript API pre-processing the file in memory before passing to rollup.

#### browserify example
```js
const file = {path: './lib/test.js', contents: '…'}
const stream = new stream.Readable()
const filePath = path.parse(process.cwd() + '/' + file.path)
stream.push(file.contents);
stream.push(null);

//send alterred file stream to browserify
browserify(stream, {basedir: filePath.dir}).transform(babelTransform, {
  filename: file.path,
  global: true,
  presets: [babelEnv, babelStage3]
})
```

#### rollup suggestion
```js
const file = {path: './lib/test.js', contents: '…'}
const stream = new stream.Readable()
const filePath = path.parse(process.cwd() + '/' + file.path)
stream.push(file.contents);
stream.push(null);

rollup({basedir: filePath.dir, input: stream})
```

Module import should be relative to the `basedir` attribute declared in this case, however, as Browserify, it's also possible to set a `files` array option with pre-processed cached files that can be referenced instead of physical ones. But for this case, I believe [rollup-plugin-vinyl](https://github.com/operandom/rollup-plugin-vinyl) could mimic this already.


## Update
I just stumbled on #762 which resolves the Javascript API issue, but also can be solved using [rollup-plugin-memory](https://github.com/TrySound/rollup-plugin-memory)

**Good news!** It is possible to pipe stdin into rollup. 🎉 

Here’s a plugin that carefully assigns the stdin to unique SHAs.

```mjs
// rollup-plugin-stdin
import { createHash } from 'crypto';

const { create, hasOwnProperty } = Object;

/**
* A rollup plugin to accept stdin input
* @param {{ prefix: String, stdin: NodeJS.ReadStream }} [options] plugin configuration
* @param {String} options.prefix - the string prefixed to stdin ids
* @param {NodeJS.ReadStream} options.stdin - the connected stdin stream
*/
export default function plugin ({ prefix = plugin.file, stdin = process.stdin } = {}) {
  // create stdin cache
  const cache = create(null);

  return {
    // cache stdin if the id is the plugin file, otherwise continue
    resolveId: id => id === plugin.file ? new Promise((fulfill, reject) => {
      // create a hash and array for stdin data
      const hash = createHash('sha1'), data = [];

      // stream stdin data into the array
      stdin.setEncoding('utf8').on('data', data.push.bind(data)).on('end', () => {
        // resolve the hash which is now assigned the data
        const id = prefix + hash.update(...data).digest('base64');

        cache[id] = data.join('');

        fulfill(id);
      }).on('error', reject);
    }) : null,
    // return data with a matching hash, otherwise continue
    load: id => hasOwnProperty.call(cache, id) ? cache[id] : null
  }
}

plugin.file = new String('stdin:');
```

Here is how it might be configured:

```mjs
// rollup.config.js
import stdin from 'rollup-plugin-stdin';

export default {
  input: stdin, // or input: { file: stdin.file }
  plugins: [
    stdin() // , more, plugins, etc
  ]
}
```

And here is how it might be used today for CLI piping:

```sh
echo 'export default "hello world"' | npx rollup -c -f cjs
```

Which might output:

```
'use strict';

var wyw508_ = "hello world";

module.exports = wyw508_;
```

If this seems suitable and there are no major issues, I will gladly publish this plugin.
